<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"><a href="//dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/category/legal/">LEGAL/REGULATORY &#187;</a></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><img width="75" height="75" border="0" alt="Joseph Dear, Calpers Investment Chief, Dies at 62" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/27/business/dealbook/dbpix-dear/dbpix-dear-square320.jpg"/><span class="title">Joseph Dear, Calpers Investment Chief, Dies at 62 <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Mr. Dear, the chief investment officer of the California Public Employeesâ Retirement System, restored the pension fund to health after the financial crisis.<br /><span class="elsewhere"><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/27/joseph-dear-calpers-investment-chief-dies-at-62/">DealBook &#187;</a></span></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">Another Lesson From the Fedâs Crisis Transcripts <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> The release of the transcripts of the Federal Open Market Committee meetings offers an opportunity to look at how analysis of the government decision-making process is changing, writes David Zaring in an Another View column.<br /><span class="elsewhere"><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/27/another-lesson-from-the-feds-crisis-transcripts/">DealBook &#187;</a></span></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">Fed Faced Curse of Unanimity During Crisis <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> The Federal Reserveâs failures in 2008 may have been rooted in cultural handicaps including a homogeneous group of decision makers and a distaste for disagreements, Binyamin Appelbaum writes in the Economix blog.<br /><span class="elsewhere"><a href="//economix.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/27/the-curse-of-unanimity/?ref=economy"> NEW YORK TIMES ECONOMIX </a></span></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">A Dire Economic Forecast Based on New Assumptions <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> This yearâs economic forecasts from the Congressional Budget Office were worse than last yearâs because the office stopped treating the recent slow years as outliers, Floyd Norris writes in the High &#038; Low Finance column.<br /><span class="elsewhere"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/business/economy/questioning-a-dire-economic-forecast.html?ref=business"> NEW YORK TIMES</a></span></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><img width="75" height="75" border="0" alt="A World Tour for Restructuring Enthusiasts" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/27/business/dealbook/dbpix-debt/dbpix-debt-square320.jpg"/><span class="title">A World Tour for Restructuring Enthusiasts <span class="divider">&nbsp;|&nbsp;</span></span><!-- end .title --> Thereâs something for everyone now in the world of restructuring and bankruptcy, including bailouts, bond deals and looming Chapter 11 filings, Stephen J. Lubben writes in the In Debt column.<br /><span class="elsewhere"><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/27/a-world-tour-for-restructuring-enthusiasts/">DealBook &#187;</a></span></p>
